<?php

// from https://cs.chromium.org/chromium/src/chromeos/test/data/network/encrypted.onc?dr&q=encrypted.onc&sq=package:chromium
$salt[0] = base64_decode("LvO2ljvR4LY=");
$iterations[0] = 20000;
$iv[0] = base64_decode("ugpkaONKt34MfDu511WSqQ==");
$hmac[0] = base64_decode("vFzwTgOCx3OOWwYUOSxWx0iu1LM=");
$ciphertext[0] = base64_decode("");
$password[0] = "test0000";

// one of my own
$salt[1] = "B73HAsyJIBMe";
$iterations[1] = 20000;
$iv[1] = base64_decode("yLqbN2PBM33Q0RhZuRtYJA==");
$hmac[1] = base64_decode("ps2yUXR+w9n+Y90oXivP6rt62hU=");
$ciphertext[1] = base64_decode("");
$password[1] = "eECCzF";

for ($i = 0; $i < count($salt); $i = $i+1) {
    $encryption_key = hash_pbkdf2("sha1", $password[$i], $salt[$i], $iterations[$i], 32, TRUE); // the spec is not clear about the algo. Source code in Chromium makes clear it's AES. But that appears unsupported by PHP???
    $decrypted = openssl_decrypt($ciphertext[$i], 'AES-256-CBC', $encryption_key, OPENSSL_RAW_DATA, $iv[$i]);
    $encrypted = openssl_encrypt($decrypted, 'AES-256-CBC', $encryption_key, OPENSSL_RAW_DATA, $iv[$i]);
    $again = openssl_decrypt($encrypted, 'AES-256-CBC', $encryption_key, OPENSSL_RAW_DATA, $iv[$i]);

    if ($ciphertext[$i] == $encrypted && $decrypted == $again && json_decode($decrypted) != NULL && $hmac[$i] == hash_hmac("sha1", $ciphertext[$i], $encryption_key, TRUE)) {
        echo "Test case $i: all good.";
        continue;
    }
    echo "Test case $i: something's fishy.";
//    echo $ciphertext[$i];
//    echo $decrypted;
//    echo $encrypted;
//    echo $again;
    echo "Calculated b(HMAC) = ".base64_encode(hash_hmac("sha1", $ciphertext[$i], $encryption_key, TRUE)).", filed b(HMAC) = ".base64_encode($hmac[$i])."\n";
}
